I think we're all actually agreeing here. Here's what happens with these kinds of things, imo:

1. Card is printed and found that it can be broken by cEDH/Spike types.
2. 984517 variations of that deck are made until the "best" version is decided upon. Almost none of these are actually made, but rather just added to the database.
3. People that aren't brewers look for popular decks, and actually build them.
4. Those folks then become one of two things, a shocking amount of the time. Johnny's who play solitaire while not noticing that the table is bored, or PubStompers who don't care.
It's unfortunate, but it doesn't incriminate those who actually take the time to build their own thing.

I do think it’s right to be disappointed that the [insert mechanic] commander turns out to be more optimal when it’s built to use [insert mechanic] for a purpose other than its intended use. That does really blow
